  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing robust internal control systems\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n4. Training\n- Educating employees about money laundering risks\n- Training staff to recognize suspicious activities\n- Maintaining ongoing compliance knowledge\n\n5. Transaction Monitoring\n- Tracking unusual financial patterns\n- Implementing automated detection systems\n- Investigating potential money laundering indicators\n\n6. Penalties for Non-Compliance\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal investigations\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and help law enforcement track potentially illegal financial activities.",
